05:30.900 --> 05:38.200
So the title of your 2022 paper nicely sums up some of the main topics that we want to talk about today,

05:38.200 --> 05:44.100
namely democratic economic planning, social metabolism, and the environment.

05:44.100 --> 05:48.900
How do these fields relate to each other and why is it important to bring them together?

05:48.900 --> 05:54.200
And maybe since some of my listeners might not be familiar with the concept,

05:54.200 --> 06:00.100
maybe you could start by explaining social metabolism as a concept and idea.

06:00.100 --> 06:09.300
Yes. So the expression social metabolism is used to refer to the biophysical dimension of economic processes.

06:09.300 --> 06:13.800
And so when we talk about the metabolism of organisms,

06:13.800 --> 06:22.100
it's the process by which they create and maintain their structure by exchanging materials and energy with their environment.

06:22.100 --> 06:29.700
And so as an analogy, the social metabolism refers to the flows of matter and energy used to sustain material stocks.

06:29.700 --> 06:39.900
And so material stocks include both human bodies and also material artifacts that are used by society.

06:39.900 --> 06:43.700
And so we think, and in general, in ecological economics,

06:43.700 --> 06:49.500
that understanding the economy as a social metabolism provides a particular lens

06:49.500 --> 06:56.900
that can be very helpful in analyzing the biophysical reality of economic structures.

06:56.900 --> 07:02.600
And then it also sees the economic process with its four points,

07:02.600 --> 07:10.200
the points of extraction, production, consumption, and waste and dissipation to get outside from the dichotomy

07:10.200 --> 07:15.200
that is often there in economic analysis of only having production and consumption.

07:15.200 --> 07:20.300
What is also very useful with the social metabolism is that it has accounting frameworks

07:20.300 --> 07:25.300
that can help us to analyze in a very systematic ways the throughput of matter and energy.

07:25.300 --> 07:36.000
And then it also has databases that exist right now to help us understand how economies have right now,

07:36.000 --> 07:38.900
of course, also an ecological aspect to it.

07:38.900 --> 07:48.500
And then it's also this accounting aspects that make us think about the ways we could make use of this into planning and democratic planning.

07:48.500 --> 07:52.300
And so how do these fields relate to each other?

07:52.300 --> 08:01.100
We think that in the context where we are urgently looking for ways to account for ecological realities in the way we organize the economy,

08:01.100 --> 08:07.200
we think the framework of social metabolism could be of great use in the coordination of economic processes

08:07.200 --> 08:15.200
and that if we are to coordinate economic processes in a way that is both ecologically sustainable and socially just,

08:15.200 --> 08:18.400
we will have to plan it democratically.

08:18.500 --> 08:27.000
And so one of the also important issues highlighted by the ecological crisis is the issue of scale.

08:27.000 --> 08:36.800
And that relates to how big the economy is in relation to its natural environment and how much pressure we are exerting on it.

08:36.800 --> 08:44.700
And so then ecological economics, also based on the work of Herman Daly, have stressed the importance of this question

08:44.800 --> 08:54.700
and the fact that it has to be addressed on its own since it cannot be addressed indirectly by tackling issues of allocation and distribution, for example.

08:54.700 --> 09:00.800
So to reach sustainability, we have to collectively give ourselves ways to act upon the scale.

09:00.800 --> 09:03.900
And so that first means being able to assess it.

09:03.900 --> 09:13.100
And so the approach of social metabolism provides, according to us, the language to discuss and to represent the biophysical scale of the economy.

09:13.100 --> 09:22.500
Fantastic. And so basically, as I understand it, we need to find different ways through which we can address this question of social metabolism,

09:22.500 --> 09:27.600
because the way we address it right now is basically catastrophic, so to speak.

09:27.600 --> 09:36.200
And I mean, of course, the people who are working in the field of democratic economic planning have already heard of this catastrophe

09:36.200 --> 09:41.600
and tried to incorporate the question of ecological planning into their models.

09:41.700 --> 09:52.000
And you look at models by Devine and Adamann, by Kotrick and Cottrell, David Leibman, and as well as Paracon developed by Hanel and Albert.

09:52.000 --> 10:01.200
And so you notice that they try to include this question of ecology into their models, but that they do not do it sufficiently, that they lack.

10:01.200 --> 10:10.000
You already mentioned the question of scale and that they have a framework through which this inclusion of the question of ecology

10:10.000 --> 10:13.500
can actually not succeed at the end.

10:13.500 --> 10:17.000
So maybe you could tell us why you think that this is the case.

10:17.000 --> 10:24.500
Let's take the three canonical models, or I don't know how to call them, but the three models from the from the 90s.

10:24.500 --> 10:29.500
So Devine, Adamann, Kotrick and Cottrell, and Albert and Hanel.

10:29.500 --> 10:36.400
Devine and Adamann, they are talking a lot about the question of environment in their recent work.

10:36.400 --> 10:38.900
They are really preoccupied by this question.

10:38.900 --> 10:40.400
Obviously, they are.

10:40.400 --> 10:47.000
And their answer is, in fact, quite simple and probably a very interesting answer.

10:47.000 --> 10:50.200
It's just they don't give much detail about it.

10:50.200 --> 10:56.200
They are telling us the way we envision the functioning of the economy.

10:56.200 --> 11:06.300
And mostly, as probably your listeners know already, Devine and Adamann are focusing mostly on investment in their model.

11:06.300 --> 11:11.600
And he said, with what we propose, we will have a conscious humanity,

11:11.600 --> 11:21.200
we'll have a conscious understanding of what we are doing collectively in terms of investment and its impact on the environment.

11:21.200 --> 11:24.100
And therefore, we can take the best decisions.

11:24.100 --> 11:27.900
We agree with this, like it's possible that that we reach that.

11:27.900 --> 11:36.900
But the question of how we will be conscious of the impact of our decision on the environment is not always clear,

11:36.900 --> 11:41.500
and at least for us in Devine and Adamann's model.

11:41.500 --> 11:47.100
And it's a lot about we should talk about it in negotiation.

11:47.100 --> 11:49.900
Their model is called negotiated coordination.

11:49.900 --> 11:51.700
There's a reason for that.

11:51.700 --> 11:57.300
We should negotiate about it in meetings and therefore take the best decision.

11:57.300 --> 12:06.000
We think that indicators and models of how the social metabolism, for example,

12:06.000 --> 12:10.300
functions would be helpful to know about this.

12:10.300 --> 12:13.500
So that's the first problem we have.

12:13.500 --> 12:17.900
About Kokchet and Cottrell, the answer is even simpler.

12:17.900 --> 12:23.700
In their main book from 1993, Toward a New Socialism,

12:23.700 --> 12:27.700
they mostly say, well, environment is a political question.

12:27.700 --> 12:32.700
We don't fix this through market indicators or prices.

12:32.700 --> 12:41.200
We fix this through political discussion, which comes quite a lot close to what Devine and Adamann are saying.

12:41.200 --> 12:49.900
But it's even, I'd say, bigger in terms of what they imply is that we should fix that by referenda.

12:49.900 --> 12:58.300
Or what we think is that a lot of questions, in fact, involve the ecological question.

12:58.300 --> 13:06.200
And so if for each issue we have to make a referenda, we'll have a lot of referenda.

13:06.200 --> 13:12.600
So we think that there should be an easier way to take those decisions.

13:12.600 --> 13:18.700
I'm not talking about Michael Albert for participatory economics

13:18.700 --> 13:26.100
because Robin Hannell has developed his specific answers much deeply in recent work,

13:26.100 --> 13:31.400
like from 2017 to a book published last year.

13:31.400 --> 13:34.400
And his answer is twofold, I'd say.

13:34.400 --> 13:45.600
First, on one side, he has a way to locate ecological damage that has been done to a community and for this community to be compensated.

13:45.700 --> 13:56.800
I won't go into details to that, but mostly the goal is for people who receive harm from pollution to get some compensation,

13:56.800 --> 14:03.000
which is all right in itself, like it's not a bad thing to do, but it's quite limited.

14:03.000 --> 14:11.700
And it does not at all the question of the environmental equilibrium that we need to reach and to live in harmony with.

14:11.700 --> 14:20.800
On the other side, which is more interesting on that level, he proposes development plans at the level of the environment.

14:20.800 --> 14:28.800
But here again, as for the two precedent models, he does not offer how we would do this and from which point of view

14:28.800 --> 14:37.000
and how his shadow prices, for example, are helping us to understand what is the state of the environment right now.

14:37.000 --> 14:43.900
In fact, in his recent book, he takes one or two sentences to tell us there will be a ministry of environment.

14:43.900 --> 14:48.600
He'll take care of providing the data and we'll go from there.

14:48.600 --> 14:52.800
That's all right. But let's say if I'm being generous,

14:52.800 --> 15:01.700
I would say that we would like to know how this ministry will function and on which data it will base its decision and reflections.

15:01.700 --> 15:10.900
So that's where we come in, saying that we need to have a broader vision, mostly based on what Sophie just told you.

15:10.900 --> 15:20.100
Fantastic. So let's take a closer look at this broader vision of what we could base our decisions on, basically.

15:20.100 --> 15:30.600
So it seems as if what you are proposing is that we should go for developing a better idea of the throughput of matter and energy

15:30.600 --> 15:35.600
and how this relates to the social worlds that we engage with.

15:35.600 --> 15:43.200
And of course, it would be absolutely helpful to get a clearer picture of how these two things relate to each other.

15:43.200 --> 15:51.200
So maybe you could go into how you approach your own framework, how you think that these measurements,

15:51.200 --> 16:02.400
these data points also of material throughput and energy can help us with developing alternative ideas of democratic planning.

16:02.400 --> 16:06.800
Well, I'll try to be simple because the idea is quite simple.

16:06.800 --> 16:11.800
How we will do it will be complicated, but what we want to do is quite simple.

16:11.800 --> 16:14.700
First, we have to build a representation.

16:14.800 --> 16:26.900
That's what Sophie was talking about, a representation of how this social metabolism works and is in relationship with the rest of the environment around it.

16:26.900 --> 16:28.900
So that's the first thing we have to do.

16:28.900 --> 16:36.200
And that's a theoretical, that's like an abstract representation that will help us understand what's happening.

16:36.200 --> 16:38.000
This does not exist right now.

16:38.000 --> 16:47.900
Like there's no way for the moment in the capitalist system we live in to know exactly what are those interactions.

16:47.900 --> 16:55.800
Friends around the world are trying to do this and are trying to build such a representation, but it does not exist at the moment.

16:55.900 --> 17:08.100
Then we think we should think about the long-term planning of society in terms of what we have called in a recent paper, socio-metabolic planning.

17:08.100 --> 17:19.500
So the notion we are developing here is that long-term development and long-term vision of our society should be integrated.

17:19.600 --> 17:43.400
So when, for example, Devine and Adamann are talking about investment planning, which all the others also do, we should, when we do this, take into consideration what will be the relationship of what we will do and what do we want for nature around us and how we want to develop inside the environment.

17:43.900 --> 17:59.000
So this is kind of a vision of social ecology, if we can say like it's an understanding of us as inside a first nature that has to develop, that has to be maintained in equilibrium.

17:59.000 --> 18:11.800
And also, we want to see where we want to go as a society inside that and when we want our planet to go in terms of the development of its environment.

18:11.900 --> 18:18.000
So this is the kind of planning we want to import into democratic planning.

18:18.600 --> 18:30.400
Our message to the democratic planning gang is to say we have to include all of this in our planning, not just what humans do.

18:31.100 --> 18:35.500
We have to include what's happening to the environment and our relationship to all that.

18:35.800 --> 18:43.200
And to the economic, the ecological economics gang, we're saying, well, we have to do all this democratically.

18:43.600 --> 18:54.000
It's through democratic planning that we can attain that, not through some kind of technocratic decisions, decision-making that would not be the best way to reach our objective.

18:54.300 --> 18:59.000
So this is kind of the two messages we're trying to send on both ways.

18:59.000 --> 19:11.700
And on that, for example, one of our members, Bengi Agbulut, wrote a very interesting text in Ecological Economics a few years ago, telling them, well, maybe we have to take to understand what's that.

19:11.700 --> 19:20.900
And she wrote it with Fikret Adaman, who was a non-divine partner in this project that they have about democratic planning.

19:21.400 --> 19:32.800
So they wrote this article saying to the Ecological Economics group, well, you have to look at what's happening on democratic planning side, because those two worlds have to come together.

19:32.900 --> 19:34.100
And that's what we're trying to do.

19:34.700 --> 19:45.100
So in order to kind of merge these worlds of ecological economics and democratic planning, we will need to have some elements that come together.

19:45.600 --> 19:50.200
And you describe a couple of them within your paper.

19:50.700 --> 20:06.400
You quite clearly state that we will need to construct deliberative planning institutions, that we will need to institutionalize non-reductionist categories that express social metabolism in biophysical and ecological terms instead of output terms.

20:06.800 --> 20:20.200
And you say that we need to create a framework to manage the biophysical scale of the throughput and the nature of ecological relations inherent in the social metabolism of a post-capitalist society to come.

20:20.500 --> 20:24.800
So there are a couple of things we need to build, so to speak.

20:25.100 --> 20:47.000
Maybe let's start with looking at the alternative indicators, because Simon, you already mentioned many of the models right now do propose things in very broad terms, but still sometimes they lack a concrete idea of how we could get to implementing those ideas.

20:47.000 --> 20:55.700
And crucially also, they lack indicators that might serve as a basis for the collective decision making.

20:55.700 --> 21:02.600
So we will need to develop indicators that are not based on market prices as it is done right now.

21:02.600 --> 21:08.900
And we can see how absolutely catastrophic the outcome of this mechanism is.

21:09.300 --> 21:14.100
So you detail that market prices are absolutely not the right way to go.

21:14.400 --> 21:16.700
But what are the indicators that we need?

21:16.700 --> 21:28.100
What are the alternative indicators that you propose that can represent these biophysical relations to the social metabolism better than markets can?

21:28.400 --> 21:32.100
So what do we have to develop in order to get there?

21:32.600 --> 21:32.900
Right.

21:32.900 --> 21:39.700
Well, of course, that's a complicated question, and that will vary depending on what we're talking about.

21:40.300 --> 21:50.100
Raising tomatoes won't be the same as organizing a whole ecosystem in some cases, or mining some other resources, right?

21:50.100 --> 21:53.300
So different sectors will require different sets of indicators.

21:53.300 --> 22:02.400
But the broad idea here is that, as you say, market prices are not adequate to address this for a variety of reasons.

22:02.800 --> 22:10.600
And currently, of course, what we have is we have plenty of planning and capitalism, but it's largely around financial imperatives.

22:11.000 --> 22:17.800
And therefore, like from units, which every time they can pawn costs on other people.

22:18.100 --> 22:20.500
So then those prices don't account for that.

22:20.800 --> 22:29.200
But beyond that, even if we were to say, okay, like we're in a different system anyway, can't we just sit together,

22:29.200 --> 22:36.500
figure out priorities and then put a set of prices and have people interact around that, there's even an issue with that.

22:36.500 --> 22:49.500
And that's like prices or financial quantities, we think, cannot represent like the whole diversity, the whole variety of things we need to care about.

22:49.900 --> 23:01.600
So there's this concept in ecological economics, the incommensurability, sorry for the pronunciation, of those different dimensions that cannot be put on a single scale.

23:01.600 --> 23:04.100
So there's no way to get prices right in a sense.

23:04.100 --> 23:06.800
We know market prices don't do a good job.

23:07.300 --> 23:16.300
But there's also no single set of right prices that could do a right job, which is why Simone was talking about shadow prices before.

23:16.700 --> 23:19.200
We'll need prices for some stuff, probably.

23:19.600 --> 23:25.600
There are going to be some zones where people interact around those prices and that'll be fine.

23:25.900 --> 23:35.600
But we'll also need all sorts of indicators to understand what kind of impact our actions, our interaction with the environment are having.

23:35.600 --> 23:40.000
Coming back to my tomatoes, for example, we'll need an indicator of water usage.

23:40.500 --> 23:42.300
That's not a price, that's a quantity.

23:42.400 --> 23:48.800
There's no way to get a price of that and then hope that interactions will get us to the right quantity.

23:49.700 --> 23:59.600
It's a quantity and we'll need to figure out what kind of total water usage we want for our culture, what kind of what amount we want for tomatoes, et cetera, et cetera.

24:00.000 --> 24:02.900
And I think we might get to this question later on.

24:02.900 --> 24:08.700
But of course, this also influences how we see products that might come from outside the community as well.

24:09.300 --> 24:18.600
So there's going to be a whole different accounting in terms of just not just equating the lowest cost or whatever when we think about trade or things like that.

24:18.900 --> 24:25.500
So that's the broad idea to have this multiplicity of indicators, biophysical indicators, some prices.

24:25.500 --> 24:36.700
And I would add maybe a third category of social and political indicators related to what we want, what we wish, for example, in terms of basic needs.

24:36.900 --> 24:38.900
Are we reaching those basic needs?

24:38.900 --> 24:40.200
How are we doing it?

24:40.200 --> 24:42.600
How are we attaining this, et cetera?

24:42.600 --> 24:48.400
So again, the specifics will have to vary in terms of sectors, in terms of industry.

24:48.400 --> 24:49.900
But that would be the broad idea.

24:50.300 --> 24:59.000
Maybe let's dig a little bit deeper there, because I mean, for me, it's easy to imagine a scenario in which we are provided with these additional indicators.

24:59.400 --> 25:12.500
This is happening already in capitalist contexts where life cycle analysis or something like that might provide ideas about what kind of resources went into a certain product.

25:12.500 --> 25:14.700
So this is kind of happening right now.

25:15.200 --> 25:20.200
However, you write that the tools that you propose could be used to, and I quote you here,

25:30.000 --> 25:30.800
End quote.

25:31.200 --> 25:51.500
So this, of course, sounds very, very exciting, but still I need some more elements in order to get a clear idea of how we can come to a coherent set of mechanisms, so to speak, that will together form a political economy based on this ecological paradigm.

25:51.800 --> 26:17.800
So maybe you could help me paint this picture in my head in order to get a better idea of how these different elements that you propose can become factors when it comes to the active coordination of an economy instead of being an additional factor of information that is also supplied in capitalist contexts today.

26:18.400 --> 26:32.500
Yes, so that's a very good question, and I think let's maybe start by going back to what Simon talked about, the long-term economic planning, the long-term metabolic planning as well.

26:32.900 --> 26:45.800
I think the thing is social metabolic planning will be done to organize need satisfaction and also in the context of defined planetary boundaries.

26:46.200 --> 27:00.700
But then the thing is, we will have to establish a long-term social objective regarding society-nature relation that is in relation to defined planetary boundaries, but are not the planetary boundaries themselves.

27:01.000 --> 27:14.200
So it's important to distinguish between the social objective and the planetary boundary that is not seen as an objective limit to social action, but rather as an important guide to democratic debates.

27:14.800 --> 27:38.800
And so then we establish a social objective that comes together with certain indicators that can be quantified in terms of certain accounting frameworks from the social metabolism, for example, that can help us to track and see how are we doing in front of these long-term goals.

27:39.700 --> 27:57.200
So we have some of these long-term objectives that are socially set, but then we have to relate that as well to this day-to-day and year-to-year organization of economic processes.

27:57.500 --> 28:09.500
So then, secondly, we can see the use of social metabolic indicators in relation to regulation, so exposed, like you first said.

28:09.700 --> 28:26.200
So to monitor, expose the progress relating to the social objectives and to see with indicators from the social metabolism, but also with a whole set of other biophysical indicators, how we are doing in relation to our goals in the long-term,

28:26.200 --> 28:37.300
but also related to how it is going right now and to understand how it's going in comparison to what we thought it would be going right now in relation to ecological limits.

28:37.600 --> 28:41.100
And at this point, there would be a ton of data.

28:41.500 --> 29:00.700
And so that's also a very important thing that we will have to think about people in certain workspaces that will be dedicated to problematize metabolic issues in production processes, but also to formulate the synthesis of this data into useful indicators.

29:01.400 --> 29:11.800
And then that brings us to the third step or the third way of envisioning the role of social metabolism in more of an active coordination, what you were asking about.

29:12.400 --> 29:29.500
And so we want to plan the next year's production and consumption by taking into account, first, where the last year stands according to the long-term social targets, and also second, the ecological implications of particular products and methods of production.

29:30.300 --> 29:54.300
And so this means that we are looking at where we stand, how we thought it would go and how it did go in the end to see where we are now and to plan for the future for the next year and readjust the social target according to the scientific knowledge that exists on ecological limits and planetary boundaries.

29:54.800 --> 30:07.100
Then we can use metabolic data related to specific products, like you said, regarding by doing life cycle analysis, and then to assess their material use throughout their whole life cycle.

30:07.900 --> 30:21.800
And using this data to see, for example, specific products, how their production and their consumption would affect the social metabolism during the next year to come.

30:22.100 --> 30:33.300
And then to see how products and particular infrastructures, for example, can lock us into a specific path of resource use for the next year, but also for the years to come.

30:33.600 --> 30:48.400
And to see how, for example, how constructing specific types of buildings and specific types of transport infrastructures will have impacts on the ecological impacts of the economy for many years.

30:48.700 --> 31:00.100
And then we're talking a lot about these indicators related to social metabolism, but it would be also necessary to use a variety of indicators and sources of knowledge as well to do so.

31:00.100 --> 31:15.500
And so we have to discuss also metabolic flows in relation to their place within provisioning systems and to see how these ecological flows are related to other social processes.

31:15.800 --> 31:28.300
And to see as well, for example, how they're organized to fulfill some specific needs and also how they are related to different kinds of meanings for different people and for different groups in the economy.

31:28.300 --> 31:36.800
And all of this have to be discussed at different levels in order to integrate these different kinds of information.

31:37.700 --> 31:50.300
And so the idea is that we can give all the relevant information, for example, by having synthesis that are done by some groups and workspaces that are dedicated to that.

31:50.300 --> 32:01.700
And to give this information to people in structured deliberations and decision making to have a mix of decisions that are made democratically,

32:01.900 --> 32:08.200
but also some data based decision making that is done more on a day to day basis.

32:09.400 --> 32:20.900
So I gave three different examples that the idea is that we have several levels of planning and monitoring to set objectives and to follow our progress in relation to these objectives.

32:21.400 --> 32:34.800
And maybe just to say it in another way, in fact, the larger metabolic planning acts like a constraint on the annual and day to day planning.

32:34.800 --> 32:44.900
It tells us, OK, we have this larger goal we want to reach, like we don't want to reach that threshold of biodiversity, for example, on the planet.

32:44.900 --> 32:51.600
Hence, we have to reduce the emission of this pollutant that kills that animal and that part of the world.

32:52.800 --> 33:03.600
So if we don't want to use that pollutant, this gives us an indicator saying, OK, we have this maximum of emission that we can emit from that pollutant.

33:03.700 --> 33:09.300
How do we give the permission, the amount of emission we can give?

33:09.300 --> 33:11.500
How do we distribute it?

33:11.500 --> 33:20.300
And how do we prioritize to which kind of production process we will allow to emit that pollutant?

33:20.300 --> 33:26.100
And that comes into annual and day to day work, annual planning and day to day work.

33:26.200 --> 33:37.100
That's what I meant by it's kind of a constraint that we're putting on our planning when doing the metabolic planning, the long term metabolic planning.

33:37.100 --> 33:50.400
Very, very interesting, I have to say, because I was recently also on a workshop in Berlin where somebody did a really, really great presentation on how life cycle analysis could be fed into democratic planning.

33:50.400 --> 34:05.900
And one thing that he stressed is that since the tool is not that complex, it would allow for a form of bottom up planning as well, in which you would have these constraints that you talked about, Simon.

34:05.900 --> 34:17.600
And then people within the different socialist enterprises, for example, would be able to feed in the data from the ground to the informational system through life cycle analysis.

34:17.900 --> 34:22.100
And therefore, we would have a combination of central and decentral elements.

34:22.100 --> 34:29.600
And so I think this is a really, really, really interesting way to approach the whole thing that you that you sketch.

34:29.600 --> 34:32.300
Nonetheless, there are, of course, open questions.

34:32.300 --> 34:41.700
So one would be, do you have a bit of an idea of the specific mechanisms and also institutions that one would need in order to make this happen?

34:41.700 --> 34:50.100
Because, Simon, you already mentioned we would have to come to a workable set of constraints.

34:50.100 --> 34:56.200
We would have, of course, a different informational base in order to deliberate about these questions.

34:56.200 --> 35:06.800
But still, I mean, at the end, we would have to have global constraints on our social metabolism and we would have to agree upon these global constraints.

35:06.800 --> 35:12.500
And this is, of course, kind of a difficult thing to get to.

35:12.500 --> 35:21.000
So do you have an idea of different mechanisms or institutions that might help with such a small task?

35:21.000 --> 35:27.200
I wouldn't answer straight away, because I think it is quite an important question.

35:27.200 --> 35:38.300
It is definitely one of the key challenges to coordinate the scope of decision making in regard to the scale of ecological impacts,

35:38.300 --> 35:50.000
because, of course, every economic, social economic decision has an ecological impact or an ecological dimension to it.

35:50.000 --> 35:54.900
And then, of course, local decisions also have global impacts.

35:54.900 --> 36:06.300
And, of course, then, I guess global decisions, if we take all of it together, of course, has impacts in a very differentiated way in different places.

36:06.300 --> 36:13.000
And so I would say we do not have specific institutions right now to propose.

36:13.000 --> 36:36.400
And I guess it is open for creativity and discussion outside from the fact that we will have to coordinate these different levels of decision making in having global goals and also specific local targets and monitoring at these different scales.

36:36.400 --> 36:40.200
I don't know if someone else wanted to add something regarding that.

36:40.200 --> 36:49.100
Yeah, I think what you just mentioned there, that we don't have specific institution, that's coming back to the presentation of our group in the beginning.

36:49.100 --> 37:03.500
That's also one way we like to proceed, that is not to have a specific template to say, OK, like here's if we follow from A to Z, we'll have a nice cake with democratic planning written on it at the end,

37:03.500 --> 37:18.100
but rather a set of preoccupations and sort of basic processes that are central to us and from which communities or groups of people can then design on their own institutions that can work.

37:18.100 --> 37:19.900
So that's one key thing.

37:19.900 --> 37:25.200
So we don't have a specific set up in mind.

37:25.200 --> 37:44.500
That said, I will add we can see this as sort of a hierarchy of responsibilities, both on decisions to be made in terms of production, consumption and all that with respect to the environment, but also into following some of these indicators.

37:44.600 --> 37:53.900
For example, local communities will certainly be better placed than anybody else to understand how a local ecosystem is doing.

37:53.900 --> 38:04.300
So even beyond broad biophysical indicators, just the health of an ecosystem, maybe you can see by knowing a forest, by taking a walk in it.

38:04.300 --> 38:15.100
And that's something that maybe technocrats somewhere would not be able to do, even if they had, I don't know, satellites to look at the said forest.

38:15.100 --> 38:26.900
So there's this whole source of information that will be central in the understanding of how exactly this interconnectedness is working out in practice.

38:26.900 --> 38:36.300
That's one thing. The responsibilities of following up on how targets are working and if we should rearrange them and do things differently.

38:36.300 --> 38:41.200
And also responsibilities on what kind of decisions we make.

38:41.200 --> 38:50.200
And there, I don't think there's any shortcuts that can be made from making those decisions about what's global and what's local.

38:50.200 --> 38:57.700
We'll have to discuss it, we'll have as a group to determine which is which and who gets to decide.

38:57.700 --> 39:04.100
But we can imagine a system whereby every level has inputs into what other levels do, right?

39:04.100 --> 39:15.600
Maybe some kind of federative structure, for example, where local boards or something or local decision bodies can send people to higher ones or different ones.

39:15.600 --> 39:18.100
And therefore, the information circulates.

39:18.100 --> 39:26.600
Maybe one last thing I'll say is that for this to all work, that information has to be both open and available.

39:26.600 --> 39:33.100
And that's crucial, right? That we don't have five experts somewhere who know everything about the environment.

39:33.100 --> 39:35.200
We give them a call every time we need to make a decision.

39:35.200 --> 39:37.900
But really, they're the only ones knowing what's going on, right?

39:37.900 --> 39:45.300
So it's crucial that we don't have that and that instead this information is open and it's palatable as well, right?

39:45.300 --> 40:00.300
It will have to be made in a way whereby even non-experts or people who don't have specific knowledge about a given issue can still make an informed decision about this if those democratic planning processes are to work.

40:00.300 --> 40:08.300
And maybe just to add two little things, because your question is so broad and so stimulating that we have a lot of answers.

40:08.300 --> 40:17.600
I think that in the previous models, like in the three canonical models, mostly when they were written in the 90s, it changed afterwards.

40:17.600 --> 40:21.500
But there were two answers to your question.

40:21.700 --> 40:28.700
Divine Adaman had an answer, which was, we will take decisions on the broader issues collectively.

40:28.700 --> 40:43.700
And then we will have this being sent down to different production units from a plan that we take a decision upon as a nation or as a country or as a region, whatever.

40:43.900 --> 40:54.900
But we have this level and then there are local and regional places that are receiving, OK, we've decided that at this level and then it goes down.

40:54.900 --> 41:03.900
At the opposite, Participatory Economics was saying, well, you cannot take decisions on things that do not matter to you concretely.

41:03.900 --> 41:07.900
So take decisions on what you want to produce, what you want to consume.

41:07.900 --> 41:10.900
And from that, a plan will be built.

41:11.100 --> 41:20.100
That's the contribution, I'd say, from Robin and Michael, the very interesting and stimulating idea and Participatory Economics.

41:20.100 --> 41:30.100
Both came to a place where there's more space for contribution from the other side, I'd say.

41:30.300 --> 41:38.300
Like Robin started building investment plans, development plans and all that that are of a higher level.

41:38.300 --> 41:52.300
While in the recent work by Fikret and Pat, you see a lot of things about local autonomy, democratic autonomy from the production units and all that.

41:52.500 --> 42:01.500
So we all agree in the end that there is a balance to be found in this, and that's not a big surprise, let's say.

42:01.500 --> 42:10.500
We all know that. I wrote an article on criteria about democratic planning, and one of them was COPE.

42:10.500 --> 42:20.500
And I think it's evident that we have to have our say as a participant to this economy about what's happening in our day to day work,

42:20.700 --> 42:23.700
but also on our larger objective.

42:23.700 --> 42:34.700
The day to day one is easier to think about, like we can know how we can manage, self-manage a company or, you know, a workshop or whatever.

42:35.700 --> 42:44.700
When it comes to a greater plan, a larger plan, how can we take decisions on that level clearly?

42:44.900 --> 42:48.900
As Mathieu was saying, we are not developing a model.

42:48.900 --> 42:59.900
If we are working on something, it's to go from those models to modules that will be, you know, that could be independent

42:59.900 --> 43:07.900
and that could be thought of independently from the rest of a model, and maybe that could be implemented in society

43:07.900 --> 43:12.900
when the time is not ready for other sections of the economy to be democratized.

43:13.100 --> 43:22.100
And one of the questions we're asking is what is the kind of information that we need for citizens to participate consciously

43:22.100 --> 43:31.100
and with all of the information available to them, but with not an overload of information, because that's the danger.

43:31.100 --> 43:36.100
As Sophie was saying, we can have tons of data, you know, factors and all that.

43:36.300 --> 43:46.300
But how do we take a sensible and intelligent decision on such questions and have enough data to take the decision?

43:46.300 --> 43:48.300
This is what we're working on right now.

43:48.300 --> 43:56.300
Like it's part of the reflection we are having about modules of planning and developing them.

43:56.300 --> 44:02.300
So your question was right on what we're working on right now.

44:02.500 --> 44:10.500
Excellent. I think we can even dig a little deeper because I think this is a very crucial point.

44:10.500 --> 44:16.500
So maybe we could get to a point where people can imagine what this might look like,

44:16.500 --> 44:22.500
because we have now established that there will be alternative indicators

44:22.700 --> 44:30.700
that are trying to maybe also visualize the biophysical throughput,

44:30.700 --> 44:37.700
matter and energy questions related to all kinds of materials, to labor, human labor,

44:37.700 --> 44:42.700
also animal labor, I guess, and all these different elements.

44:42.700 --> 44:46.700
So we will have a plethora of information and data.

44:46.900 --> 44:51.900
And of course, as you already mentioned, this is immediately overwhelming.

44:51.900 --> 44:56.900
So there will need to be some kind of translation as well,

44:56.900 --> 45:03.500
I guess, in order to let people take part in a meaningful way in this deliberation.

45:03.500 --> 45:08.500
So do you have an idea of what this might look like in concrete terms?

45:09.300 --> 45:16.300
So if we have this large set of information on the complete throughput,

45:16.300 --> 45:19.300
biophysical throughput on the one side,

45:19.300 --> 45:26.300
and then we have the need to come to an informational point

45:26.300 --> 45:32.300
that is usable for a broader public in order to take part in this deliberative process,

45:32.300 --> 45:35.300
how do we get these two together?

45:36.100 --> 45:41.100
What's the process that needs to take place between these two elements?

45:41.100 --> 45:45.100
Because there needs to be some kind of translation, different mechanisms,

45:45.100 --> 45:49.100
and it doesn't have to be one mechanism, I guess, but many, probably,

45:49.100 --> 45:55.100
and also different sites that allow you to engage with these different types of data

45:55.100 --> 46:02.100
and, of course, also maybe different intensities of information,

46:02.100 --> 46:09.100
some might be willing and able to kind of take in a more abstract level of information,

46:09.100 --> 46:15.100
others will need to have information that is kind of more easily accessible and stuff like that.

46:15.100 --> 46:22.100
So how can we think about this relationship between broad deliberation about these topics on the one side

46:22.100 --> 46:26.100
and the information overload on the other maybe?

46:26.100 --> 46:39.100
One thing here is that this vision of a social metabolism allows us to segment, in a sense, this decision process.

46:39.100 --> 46:47.100
That is, once we have an overall vision of what feeds into what and exactly what affects what,

46:47.100 --> 46:52.100
then we can say, okay, well, some of these decisions will really have an effect on A and B,

46:52.100 --> 46:56.100
but not really C, that's not the way it communicates.

46:56.100 --> 47:00.100
So we don't have to constantly decide on everything at once.

47:00.100 --> 47:06.100
What we want is an overall vision where we understand what feeds into what that's crucial,

47:06.100 --> 47:12.100
that is, that decisions are not made without considering the impacts on all sorts of zones

47:12.100 --> 47:15.100
and then it comes to bite us years later, right?

47:15.100 --> 47:21.100
So it's important to have the broad vision, but we don't have to make the broad decisions every single time.

47:21.100 --> 47:28.100
We can devolve some of the local decision making about forests, for example,

47:28.100 --> 47:35.100
to a local group of citizens who would be more concerned about this particular issue.

47:35.100 --> 47:41.100
And people maybe 50 kilometres down the road don't really have to have a say in that.

47:41.100 --> 47:48.100
And it actually may be better if they don't have a say because they're not directly concerned about that.

47:48.100 --> 47:55.100
So this social metabolic vision allows us to say, okay, these two decisions we'll need to make as a group

47:55.100 --> 48:01.100
and then we'll need to have data and also some information to do that.

48:01.100 --> 48:08.100
But all these other more local decisions or more regional decisions can be made at a different scale

48:08.100 --> 48:14.100
by smaller groups of people who are directly concerned within, of course, boundaries and limits

48:14.100 --> 48:17.100
that are set in the overall picture.

48:17.100 --> 48:24.100
So therefore we can imagine the segmentation of decision making so that we're not constantly making decisions that feed in,

48:24.100 --> 48:33.100
but separating it, we can make some a lot of local decisions with confidence that it fits in an overall picture

48:33.100 --> 48:42.100
and that we don't have constantly to go and feed back with this different pictures every single time we decide to take a walk or not in the forest.

48:42.100 --> 48:53.100
I'll follow on what Mathieu was talking about and answer your question in a more imaginative way, Jan, that you were suggesting.

48:53.100 --> 48:59.100
Like, how could this, what could it look like? And it's just an idea.

48:59.100 --> 49:06.100
It's not the result of research what I'm talking about, but it can give you an idea of what it could look like.

49:06.100 --> 49:13.100
Let's take two indicators that are known right now that we have access to and that we that we're familiar with.

49:13.100 --> 49:15.100
Well, at least a bit familiar with.

49:15.100 --> 49:24.100
The first one would be the nine boundaries that we should, the nine threshold that humanity should not cross for the planet not to blow up.

49:24.100 --> 49:29.100
OK, this is one known indicator that we already know about.

49:29.100 --> 49:36.100
And if we take, for example, what the OECD has done with, how they call it, Better Life Index.

49:36.100 --> 49:49.100
So that gives you an idea of how different populations in the world are living in terms of poverty rates, transport, health, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

49:49.100 --> 49:52.100
So we already have those indicators. They already exist.

49:52.100 --> 49:58.100
Let's imagine we do them better. We do them with the help of social metabolism.

49:58.100 --> 50:01.100
We have a clearer representation of all that.

50:01.100 --> 50:15.100
But we can summarize those representations into indicators of various type of indicators that give us an idea of where we are at the moment.

50:15.100 --> 50:22.100
So every five years, for example, it's just an example that the calendar and all that is just to give us an idea.

50:22.100 --> 50:38.100
Every five years, we have a broad consultation of the whole community saying this is where we are in terms of development from what we get from science and what we get from our collective work.

50:38.100 --> 50:41.100
This is the status of our relationship with nature.

50:41.100 --> 50:54.100
This is what we produce. This is the quantity of needs that are fulfilled with a few indicators, but that we think are central in terms of political decision making.

50:54.100 --> 50:59.100
We will need good designers. That will be very important.

50:59.100 --> 51:04.100
We will need people who can think about how to present data, how to do that.

51:04.100 --> 51:09.100
But those resources exist. We have that already in our society.

51:09.100 --> 51:16.100
And then we can have a broad discussion every five years, let's say, where we say, OK, where do we want to go?

51:16.100 --> 51:19.100
Where do we want those indicators to be at?

51:19.100 --> 51:24.100
Let's say we are approaching a threshold in terms of an environment question.

51:24.100 --> 51:30.100
And let's say in biodiversity, we say, OK, this threshold is we're almost there.

51:30.100 --> 51:33.100
What can we do not to reach it?

51:33.100 --> 51:43.100
Well, this would mean and then we'd have an explanation of what we should reduce in terms of consumption or in terms of production, et cetera, et cetera.

51:43.100 --> 51:47.100
And then we take a decision on where we want to go.

51:47.100 --> 52:00.100
This then translates for all sections of the community into constraints that will be put on, for example, our work unit.

52:00.100 --> 52:06.100
I am in a work collective. We are, let's say, building fridges.

52:06.100 --> 52:16.100
We are producing fridges when they told us, well, this material that you're using in your fridge, we don't think it's a priority to put it in fridge.

52:16.100 --> 52:19.100
We must use it elsewhere. We don't have much.

52:19.100 --> 52:27.100
We don't want to use much. Hence, you have to change your process or build or build less fridge.

52:27.100 --> 52:34.100
OK, then we say, what are the innovations we can make to replace that product that we don't have anymore?

52:34.100 --> 52:39.100
Or should we just propose to build less fridge because we don't have a replacement for that?

52:39.100 --> 52:48.100
And we enter that into the process, saying this is the consequences that will have this decision that we took collectively as on us.

52:48.100 --> 52:51.100
Then maybe prices for fridges will go up.

52:51.100 --> 53:05.100
Maybe we will have different type of fridges or maybe we won't have some, I don't know, specific and funny add-on that we add on our fridges that will not work anymore because we don't have the material to do it.

53:05.100 --> 53:10.100
But we will change production accordingly in our workshop.

53:10.100 --> 53:22.100
And then we will say that to others and the planning, the annual planning will take care of it in knowing that everyone is adapting, saying, oh, fridges are going up.

53:22.100 --> 53:33.100
The price of fridges are going up. Maybe I'll keep my old fridge and won't buy a new one this year because it's too expensive and I'll wait for when it breaks up before changing it.

53:34.100 --> 53:43.100
We hope everybody will do that in socialist society, but maybe they need indicators to tell them not to buy a new fridge every three years.

53:43.100 --> 53:50.100
So that's the kind of link between the two that we have to develop.

53:50.100 --> 53:57.100
And it's certain that there will be questions about how we discuss.

53:57.100 --> 54:05.100
This must be like what in a seminar that I organized about post-capitalist economies.

54:05.100 --> 54:26.100
One colleague said we will need a group of persons that are specialized in how do we take democratic decisions and that are training not only others to, let's say, facilitate discussions or organize data in a table that everyone can understand or, you know, those kind of things.

54:26.100 --> 54:32.100
But also to train people to interact in a democratic fashion and in democratic decision making.

54:32.100 --> 54:35.100
And this will be important as well.

54:35.100 --> 54:44.100
So there's a lot of culture changes that must happen for us to reach that goal of collective decision making.

54:44.100 --> 54:51.100
But we don't have to make decisions about those larger questions every two months.

54:51.100 --> 54:56.100
We can set goals and say, OK, when do we reach that goal?

54:56.100 --> 55:03.100
And maybe every year, maybe every six months, we'll find the good rhythm that's easy to find.

55:03.100 --> 55:20.100
But the idea is to have something that we take the big decision we have and we give people the right to have a slim version of the information they need or to expand like you do on a website.

55:20.100 --> 55:27.100
And have more information if they want to go down the rabbit hole and understand exactly.

55:27.100 --> 55:30.100
Yeah, but why does this thing cost more?

55:30.100 --> 55:33.100
OK, it's because we changed that and that and that.

55:33.100 --> 55:36.100
And they can go there and see if they want to.

55:36.100 --> 55:39.100
But they're not forced to do this.

55:39.100 --> 55:42.100
So we reduce information overload to do that.

55:42.100 --> 55:47.100
But we would need a very good designer for that to happen.

55:47.100 --> 56:03.100
OK, I think we will sidestep the question how you would make the decentralized actors accept the constraints that will come from a central element, because this is, of course, an important type of negotiation, let's say.

56:03.100 --> 56:19.100
So I think we sidestep this for a moment, at least in order to take one step more deeper into this question of economy-wide energy and material flow accounting, because this is kind of what you, I think, tried to sketch.

56:19.100 --> 56:33.100
I mean, at least as far as I understand it, what you're proposing is that we will really try to track the resource use of all of the materials that are involved in our social metabolism.

56:33.100 --> 56:41.100
So if, and this is maybe just to illustrate for the audience what the extent of what you're talking about, Simon, all of you talking about.

