01:21:04.100 --> 01:21:10.100
So, I mean, we kind of touched upon this, but maybe there's something to add.

01:21:10.100 --> 01:21:22.100
I think the last question already points in this direction. I would be interested in how we can bring together the different logics of different spheres.

01:21:22.100 --> 01:21:35.100
I mean, you point towards this question when you say that the different elements within the four-step process that you described, namely the points of extraction, the points of production, the points of consumption,

01:21:35.100 --> 01:21:45.100
and the points of waste, that all of these different points within the process cannot be reduced upon each other,

01:21:45.100 --> 01:21:54.100
but that they will have to be governed through different inherent logics, so to speak, but then, of course, immediately questions of translation pop up, so to speak.

01:21:54.100 --> 01:22:05.100
So how can we kind of respect the inherent logics of these different spheres while at the same time create some form of compatibility?

01:22:05.100 --> 01:22:11.100
So I guess there's a question of what's the word? Intersections.

01:22:11.100 --> 01:22:25.100
So we will need to find devices or mechanisms or political processes, or I guess these will all be political processes as well, to kind of govern these intersections between the spheres, so to speak.

01:22:25.100 --> 01:22:37.100
So maybe to kind of open up what we already talked about, because I think this is really important because right now one of the problems we have is that a certain logic,

01:22:37.100 --> 01:22:49.100
namely the logic of economic efficiency and profit maximization dominates many of the other spheres, and we would, of course, not want to reproduce this,

01:22:49.100 --> 01:23:01.100
but as I said, this leads to a point where questions of intersection and valuing the values of other logics come up, I guess.

01:23:01.100 --> 01:23:15.100
Yes, so the cohabitation of different logics, it's interesting that you put it because even in, we often say, okay, well, in our village or our community or our group, we'll do things this way.

01:23:15.100 --> 01:23:22.100
And how do we talk to the next people? Right. And that's an important question, which I'll address in one second.

01:23:22.100 --> 01:23:35.100
But what you bring up is very interesting that even within one system, if we say that we have a production logic or a logic with respect to resource use and a different one with respect to consumption,

01:23:35.100 --> 01:23:41.100
how do these things talk to each other? And I think this is a central question.

01:23:41.100 --> 01:23:52.100
So we've done some work on this. And what we've come up with is we need some kind of interface, some kind of interface in between those different realms.

01:23:52.100 --> 01:24:08.100
Or if you think back about what I was talking about with different communities, maybe what like in the current set up, we would say international trade or whatever, because we have this vision of states like doing trade with each other,

01:24:08.100 --> 01:24:20.100
which, of course, is not really what's happening, but different issue. But even if we have a given system in a locus, how does it communicate to a different system?

01:24:20.100 --> 01:24:27.100
Because we can imagine that not all at once, everybody will adopt the exact same way. And that's fine, too, right?

01:24:27.100 --> 01:24:35.100
Even in a transition towards democratic planning, we can easily imagine that one group would go one way and a different group would go in a different direction.

01:24:35.100 --> 01:24:43.100
So how could different systems communicate with each other? And from that, we'll need to have an interface.

01:24:43.100 --> 01:24:55.100
And translation can be done in one way by requiring information that the other system might not be producing in and of itself.

01:24:55.100 --> 01:25:03.100
So that's one part that's important. Just to make it easy, again, going from two communities talking to each other.

01:25:03.100 --> 01:25:11.100
Assume one is still capitalist and then in one other one, we've tried to do this kind of transition towards a democratically planned system.

01:25:11.100 --> 01:25:20.100
And we have all these biophysical indicators that we care about, but that are not explicitly taken into account in the capitalist system.

01:25:21.100 --> 01:25:38.100
How do these two communicate? Well, in order for the democratically planned economy to to really include the possibilities offered by the capitalist economy in its own planning processes,

01:25:38.100 --> 01:25:47.100
it would need to have all sorts of new information. So that interface, one of its main role in order for that translation to happen, is an information gathering role.

01:25:47.100 --> 01:25:54.100
So again, coming back to my tomatoes, if we care about water usage and in the other system, they're simply priced.

01:25:54.100 --> 01:26:03.100
They're saying we're going to sell you tomatoes for two dollars a kilogram, let's say, or perfect. Fine. Great. Good.

01:26:03.100 --> 01:26:10.100
How much water do you use? Does it take to make a kilogram of tomatoes? Because we care about that.

01:26:10.100 --> 01:26:19.100
And if we discover that it takes much more water, then that changes sort of the ratio or the actual importance we give this good.

01:26:19.100 --> 01:26:33.100
So if in our society we have a consumption target as well as a production target, then that good coming through needs to be taken into account in terms of its material flows it would generate.

01:26:33.100 --> 01:26:40.100
Right. And not only its price, so that water used in order to make it in this case.

01:26:40.100 --> 01:26:53.100
So the interface first thing gathers all the information so that the indicators that are used in the democratic economy can account for whatever is going on in the economy.

01:26:53.100 --> 01:27:00.100
At the same time, there needs to be a process designed, at least in my view, such that there's some porosity, right?

01:27:00.100 --> 01:27:04.100
There's not an isolation of a democratic system. It needs to be protected.

01:27:04.100 --> 01:27:11.100
But at some point we need to design it so that there's a bit of a competition in good practices, I would say.

01:27:11.100 --> 01:27:21.100
That is, if the system next door really is using much less water, then maybe it's interesting to get tomatoes from there rather than get tomatoes at home.

01:27:21.100 --> 01:27:29.100
If ever, for whatever reason, we feel as a society that tomatoes are very useful and are needed in that society.

01:27:29.100 --> 01:27:34.100
Once we have taken into account those biophysical indicators, social indicators as well, right?

01:27:34.100 --> 01:27:42.100
What kind of work conditions? All these indicators, once we can translate, then we can make a decision and include it in the broader processing.

01:27:42.100 --> 01:27:51.100
OK, well, we have options A, B, and C to make tomatoes at home that require arbitrage between different dimensions and all that.

01:27:51.100 --> 01:27:59.100
But there's also option D. We could get the tomatoes from next door. And here's what it means.

01:27:59.100 --> 01:28:08.100
But then if we get tomatoes from outside, what does it mean in terms of our consumption targets, in terms of our production targets as well?

01:28:09.100 --> 01:28:17.100
They'll want something for the tomatoes, right? So in the same way, we need to consider material flows in both directions.

01:28:17.100 --> 01:28:28.100
So it's a little bit the same thing. So that's one way to conceive it in between communities, I would say, with different economic systems.

01:28:28.100 --> 01:28:36.100
Because in a sense, we'll need global planning to figure out environmental problems on a global scale like carbon, as we're seeing these days.

01:28:36.100 --> 01:28:44.100
Certainly. Eventually, hopefully we'll get there. But in the meantime, a community will have power over whatever it does, right?

01:28:44.100 --> 01:28:49.100
We don't want some kind of imperialist setup, whereas, well, we're pure environmentally speaking.

01:28:49.100 --> 01:28:56.100
So we're going to tell you how to do stuff, right? This cannot be the solution in a way.

01:28:56.100 --> 01:29:05.100
So if we decide for ourselves, we set those targets, we have this interface, collect information, figure out the arbitrage, made those decisions within our own planning process.

01:29:05.100 --> 01:29:18.100
That's one way to do it. And also translate the units. In terms of your question internally, it has a similar logic with interfaces in between those different steps, I would say.

01:29:18.100 --> 01:29:25.100
But it's slightly different in that we have a broad vision of all of these moments, right?

01:29:26.100 --> 01:29:35.100
The social metabolic view says that we need to consider every single one of these moments.

01:29:35.100 --> 01:29:40.100
So one does not happen in complete isolation with the other.

01:29:40.100 --> 01:29:45.100
But to give a quick example, again, suppose we go from production to consumption.

01:29:45.100 --> 01:29:59.100
And in consumption, we have this unit of account common to everybody in common to every product that does not have to consider every single dimension every time, but that we can use some kind of currency.

01:29:59.100 --> 01:30:07.100
And in the production processes, we have all sorts of indicators that are more biophotographically based.

01:30:07.100 --> 01:30:18.100
Then we can imagine a process whereby we set boundaries and we make decisions with respect to arbitrage, with respect to resource use, before it gets to consumption, right?

01:30:18.100 --> 01:30:25.100
At which point we have a broad quantitative division of what will be available for consumption.

01:30:25.100 --> 01:30:34.100
And then allocation within the consumption moment can take place with a different currency that does not have to be linked.

01:30:34.100 --> 01:30:39.100
We'll have to talk about distribution, of course, who gets what in terms of allocation, obviously.

01:30:39.100 --> 01:30:53.100
But aside from that, we can then have a different process whereby stuff is like exchange distributed allocated according to this different unit without having this unit to talk to the other one explicitly every time.

01:30:53.100 --> 01:30:59.100
So that's a bit of this interface vision we can think of.

01:31:00.100 --> 01:31:11.100
A question that we did not yet touch upon, but that you do have work currently only in French about is the question of needs.

01:31:11.100 --> 01:31:19.100
This is, of course, again, a huge question. We are talking about a lot of huge questions today, which is great, I think.

01:31:19.100 --> 01:31:23.100
So you published a paper about the question of needs.

01:31:23.100 --> 01:31:39.100
And to me, when reading some of the bits that were kindly translated for me by Simone, I kind of got the idea that the conclusion more or less seems to be A, let's cover the basics first,

01:31:39.100 --> 01:31:49.100
and B, let's talk about what the basics are and kind of engage in a political process about this question specifically.

01:31:49.100 --> 01:31:54.100
So maybe you could walk us through your findings when it comes to the question of needs.

01:31:54.100 --> 01:31:59.100
Well, it has been a question for us since the beginning of our discussions.

01:32:00.100 --> 01:32:12.100
Needs keeps coming back at this. And I think you brought it yourself, Jan, when talking about what you thought should be covered by a universal provisioning system.

01:32:12.100 --> 01:32:19.100
This is another way of putting the question of needs at the center.

01:32:19.100 --> 01:32:25.100
What I would say is that our first question was a question of needs definition.

01:32:25.100 --> 01:32:33.100
And there's a lot that has been written on this. We made a literature review on needs and needs coverage.

01:32:33.100 --> 01:32:43.100
And not only is it talked a lot in economics, but not that much because some parts of the economic realm are not talking about needs really much.

01:32:43.100 --> 01:32:47.100
But a lot of people do and a lot of people do in other disciplines as well.

01:32:47.100 --> 01:32:52.100
Anthropology, even nursing has very interesting things to say about us.

01:32:52.100 --> 01:32:55.100
You have tons of things written about us.

01:32:55.100 --> 01:33:07.100
But the problem is that there is still this idea that we could get access to a very scientific and objective human need.

01:33:07.100 --> 01:33:20.100
So the first thing we wanted to do is debunk that idea that there is a person somewhere or a collection of people that could provide us with this is what human needs.

01:33:20.100 --> 01:33:27.100
This does not exist, obviously. Human needs are partly cultural, partly subjective.

01:33:27.100 --> 01:33:33.100
And that's all right. They are still needs. It's not because they're not objective that they're not needs.

01:33:33.100 --> 01:33:44.100
But there is another school that is saying if they are partly subjective, therefore there is no difference between needs and the rest.

01:33:44.100 --> 01:33:48.100
The needs are anything that we can desire.

01:33:48.100 --> 01:33:55.100
And we disagree, too, with this definition because we were saying, well, not really.

01:33:55.100 --> 01:34:00.100
And we all know that needs and desire are different.

01:34:00.100 --> 01:34:12.100
I can need something and if I don't have it, I'm putting myself in danger, for example, or I won't live as long as I should or, you know, I will put my health in trouble.

01:34:12.100 --> 01:34:20.100
And desires, well, it's things that I would love to have, but it's not necessary that I have them.

01:34:20.100 --> 01:34:25.100
Even though it's not objective, we know that there's a difference.

01:34:25.100 --> 01:34:37.100
And we know in the end, and that's where Nancy Fraser's text from the 90s, I think we are kind of nostalgic and work only on text from the 90s, but that's another question.

01:34:37.100 --> 01:34:53.100
We took that text from Nancy Fraser and she wrote a bunch of them about the notion that the definition of needs in our society, in capitalist society, is a struggle.

01:34:53.100 --> 01:34:57.100
There is a struggle over needs interpretation in our society.

01:34:58.100 --> 01:35:07.100
And I'm really happy that Nancy Fraser chose the word need in terms of the word rights.

01:35:07.100 --> 01:35:11.100
And I think it helps us in understanding what we're talking about.

01:35:11.100 --> 01:35:19.100
And we're not talking about human rights or natural rights where liberalism comes in and then it fucks up all the discussion.

01:35:19.100 --> 01:35:25.100
Then we need to have a discussion about what we think we need.

01:35:25.100 --> 01:35:32.100
And this discussion will be, and that's what Fraser brings in, it will be political in the end.

01:35:32.100 --> 01:35:40.100
We will have to, yes, we will be helped by science, like science has a lot of things to say about what human needs.

01:35:40.100 --> 01:35:45.100
But in the end, to agree upon something, we will have to discuss it.

01:35:45.100 --> 01:35:50.100
So it comes to what you were saying, but in a very convoluted way, but still it comes to what you were saying.

01:35:50.100 --> 01:35:58.100
It's that we have to discuss about need to select, to define what needs are in our community.

01:35:58.100 --> 01:36:08.100
But we think it will be very useful for a planning process to have that unit, to say this is what we need.

01:36:08.100 --> 01:36:17.100
This will give us what is the most basic production we must do to cover our needs.

01:36:17.100 --> 01:36:22.100
And this gives us the line Sophie in the beginning talked about two lines.

01:36:22.100 --> 01:36:28.100
One line is the planet boundaries that we cannot go over that.

01:36:28.100 --> 01:36:38.100
That's kind of our roof and the ground where we have another things we can go under is fulfilling human needs.

01:36:38.100 --> 01:36:44.100
We don't want people to die out of hunger or be in a difficult situation in terms of health.

01:36:44.100 --> 01:36:49.100
Hence, our production and consumption must be between those two lines.

01:36:49.100 --> 01:36:55.100
And we did this, Richard, to say, how do we define the bottom line?

01:36:55.100 --> 01:37:07.100
And this bottom line has to be defined politically and has to be thought of in terms of this universal provisioning that you were thinking about.

01:37:07.100 --> 01:37:16.100
Not only because, as Mathieu was saying, we need some space to make our own decision, even according to our needs.

01:37:16.100 --> 01:37:21.100
Like if you're talking about my health, yeah, I want to make a certain decision.

01:37:21.100 --> 01:37:28.100
At some point, someone will decide for me if what's best for me is to have a treatment for cancer.

01:37:28.100 --> 01:37:33.100
Well, I don't have much decisions to make. I can take it or not.

01:37:33.100 --> 01:37:36.100
But that's about it. I will not choose this treatment or this one.

01:37:36.100 --> 01:37:41.100
But when it comes to food, I can prefer apples to oranges.

01:37:41.100 --> 01:37:45.100
And I want some leeway to decide which one is better for me.

01:37:45.100 --> 01:37:53.100
Even though a nutritionist could tell me that I should eat this, I still want to have some space to decide.

01:37:54.100 --> 01:38:02.100
Hence, there is this space that we're trying to define that is not exactly this is what we need first.

01:38:02.100 --> 01:38:07.100
In terms of like chronologically, we wouldn't need to fulfill the needs.

01:38:07.100 --> 01:38:13.100
And then when all the needs of everyone are done, we'll start thinking about what we do next.

01:38:13.100 --> 01:38:18.100
Obviously, it's not that way. But we know that we cannot go under this limit.

01:38:18.100 --> 01:38:24.100
So it's to trace a limit and also to ask a very complex question.

01:38:24.100 --> 01:38:31.100
And I think I'm reading right now Simone Sutturletti and Stephen Merritt's book.

01:38:31.100 --> 01:38:35.100
And I think that they approach that question in a very interesting fashion.

01:38:35.100 --> 01:38:45.100
One that I hadn't seen before about the willingness or what they call voluntariness of fulfilling the work

01:38:45.100 --> 01:38:49.100
that has to be done for us to cover our needs.

01:38:49.100 --> 01:38:52.100
And this is a tricky question.

01:38:52.100 --> 01:39:00.100
When we put the ground level, when we said we need to have those needs fulfilled and covered,

01:39:00.100 --> 01:39:06.100
who will do the work so it is fulfilled and covered?

01:39:06.100 --> 01:39:11.100
And what do we do with the people who say, well, I don't want to work for that

01:39:11.100 --> 01:39:16.100
when we need work to be done for everyone to be able to eat?

01:39:16.100 --> 01:39:18.100
It's a tricky question.

01:39:18.100 --> 01:39:27.100
But I think that at least our research is bringing it back in when we normally try to avoid it.

01:39:27.100 --> 01:39:34.100
And I'm thinking, for example, at the three canonical models where this question is when it's treated,

01:39:34.100 --> 01:39:39.100
treated in one or two sentences and very problematically, I think.

01:39:39.100 --> 01:39:44.100
So we're bringing that back and asking the question, OK, what do we do with this?

01:39:44.100 --> 01:39:47.100
Bringing the question doesn't mean we have answers.

01:39:47.100 --> 01:39:53.100
But at least we are discussing this very specific question.

01:39:53.100 --> 01:39:56.100
And how can we focus on that?

01:39:56.100 --> 01:39:59.100
So that's where the needs in our discussion.

01:39:59.100 --> 01:40:07.100
And I think that there will be a process when the question of need will be asked politically

01:40:07.100 --> 01:40:16.100
to include more and more things, more and more services and goods in what we need

01:40:16.100 --> 01:40:20.100
from a political perspective, people will say.

01:40:20.100 --> 01:40:29.100
And at some point, I think this is the transition that we talk normally in classical socialist theory

01:40:29.100 --> 01:40:31.100
between socialism and communism.

01:40:31.100 --> 01:40:34.100
But the transition will be slow.

01:40:34.100 --> 01:40:41.100
It's the moment where we will be saying, OK, it's normal for people to have this for a living.

01:40:41.100 --> 01:40:43.100
Is it vacations?

01:40:43.100 --> 01:40:45.100
You know, we did that already.

01:40:45.100 --> 01:40:50.100
It's already in Northern society and in the global north.

01:40:50.100 --> 01:40:51.100
We did that already.

01:40:51.100 --> 01:40:53.100
This discussion already happened.

01:40:53.100 --> 01:40:59.100
But I think this will go in a larger way and it will grow with the time.

01:40:59.100 --> 01:41:04.100
But we will think about it consciously, knowing that there are limits.

01:41:04.100 --> 01:41:09.100
So it's not everybody does everything and anything he wants.

01:41:09.100 --> 01:41:17.100
It's we have to think about living harmoniously with the environment we're in.

01:41:17.100 --> 01:41:21.100
So we cannot fulfill every desire.

01:41:21.100 --> 01:41:24.100
It needs to be thought of as needs.

01:41:25.100 --> 01:41:30.100
So that's more or less the reflections we were having.

01:41:30.100 --> 01:41:35.100
And probably Sophie and Mathieu want to add things into that.

01:41:35.100 --> 01:41:37.100
I can't hear you, Sophie.

01:41:37.100 --> 01:41:41.100
Yeah, I wanted to say I didn't have anything to add for now.

01:41:41.100 --> 01:41:43.100
No, it's the same for me.

01:41:43.100 --> 01:41:45.100
I think you did a good job.

01:41:45.100 --> 01:41:50.100
OK, so there's a last question that I ask all of my guests.

01:41:50.100 --> 01:41:53.100
And it is, if you think about the future, what makes you joyful?

01:41:53.100 --> 01:41:55.100
Well, I can take a stab at that one.

01:41:55.100 --> 01:42:04.100
In a sense, for me, what makes me joyful when I think about the future is potentialities.

01:42:04.100 --> 01:42:17.100
When we think about the environment, it's really easy to get the dreary vision of the whole world disintegrating around us and this thing descending into chaos.

01:42:18.100 --> 01:42:27.100
We can think about the oft-repeated sentence that it's easier to imagine the end of the world and the end of capitalism in some ways.

01:42:27.100 --> 01:42:42.100
But at the same time, when we start looking around, what we see is people, communities collectively designing new responses every day to the challenges that come.

01:42:42.100 --> 01:42:55.100
So this human potentiality that even with challenges that we can't even think of right now, those we can see are already important enough,

01:42:55.100 --> 01:43:07.100
but that humans will be able to devise answers, to devise solutions to that, to devise unforeseen and unforeseeable response.

01:43:07.100 --> 01:43:22.100
So in a sense, the prospect of being astonished and impressed as to what we'll be able collectively to come up with to address these challenges, yeah, that would make me joyful.

01:43:22.100 --> 01:43:25.100
I had a similar answer to that.

01:43:25.100 --> 01:43:31.100
Yeah, indeed, I think for sure there'll be hard times and challenges ahead, for sure.

01:43:31.100 --> 01:43:49.100
But I think that if we think that we can organize right now and build strong solidarity networks, for sure there will be a powerful resistance to whatever will be happening and also beautiful alternatives that will emerge out of it.

01:43:49.100 --> 01:44:10.100
And I think for me, so it's not so much the fact of being surprised, but more of seeing these powerful acts of resistance and organizing and also creating these alternative prospects and alternative proposals that will necessarily happen and emerge out of this that makes me joyful.

01:44:10.100 --> 01:44:18.100
I think that when we think about the future, there's two kinds of people and I will resume that into two utopias.

01:44:18.100 --> 01:44:29.100
There is one side that is Edward Bellamy kind of side, techno utopian people that think that we will live a better life.

01:44:29.100 --> 01:44:42.100
In fact, it will be kind of a retro futuristic life where everything will be done by machines and all that, but it will be still communism and will be all equal and all that.

01:44:42.100 --> 01:44:50.100
This is more the William Morris side, News from Nowhere being the fiction I would be thinking about.

01:44:50.100 --> 01:44:59.100
And I think I'm more on this side, which is what rejoices me is that life will be simpler.

01:44:59.100 --> 01:45:26.100
I envision a world where we will have, and I won't do the classic Marx quote here, but where we will have time for just enjoying life for itself, taking time with friends, reading philosophy, discussing, and having less burden imposed by a system that is exterior to our will.

01:45:26.100 --> 01:45:36.100
And we were, yes, as my two colleagues said, we will have more of a say into it, but also more time.

01:45:36.100 --> 01:45:54.100
We have a very short amount of time on this earth. And the fact that we spend it pursuing goals that are totally, that have no consequences in terms of happiness that we have, that we give to other people around us, it's just stupid.

01:45:54.100 --> 01:46:02.100
I hope for a system where we have time to enjoy life for real and enjoying it for real is really simple, in fact.

01:46:02.100 --> 01:46:07.100
It's time with people you love. It's time with friends. It's time with learning.

01:46:07.100 --> 01:46:14.100
And I hope that a system that we build together as a humanity comes to this kind of maturity.

01:46:14.100 --> 01:46:24.100
I think that humanity can look at itself at some moment and say we could spend more time doing those things instead of pursuing the evaluation of value.

01:46:24.100 --> 01:46:26.100
Yeah, that's it.

01:46:26.100 --> 01:46:31.100
Perfect. Thank you so much for being part of Future Histories.

